WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:06.925
Atelectasis is one of the most common and
often preventable respiratory complications you'll encounter

2
00:00:06.925 --> 00:00:08.364
as a respiratory therapist.

3
00:00:09.404 --> 00:00:12.925
At its core, atelectasis is the collapse
of alveoli,

4
00:00:13.444 --> 00:00:17.784
leading to reduced or absent gas exchange
in affected areas of the lung.

5
00:00:18.424 --> 00:00:20.944
Think of it as a ventilation problem
first.

6
00:00:21.604 --> 00:00:24.625
When alveoli collapse, ventilation drops,
but

7
00:00:24.625 --> 00:00:26.524
perfusion may still be present.

8
00:00:26.934 --> 00:00:30.704
This creates a shunt-like effect, where
blood passes through

9
00:00:30.704 --> 00:00:32.744
the lungs without being oxygenated.

10
00:00:33.444 --> 00:00:33.904
The result?

11
00:00:34.564 --> 00:00:38.264
Hypoxemia that does not always respond
well to oxygen alone.

12
00:00:39.125 --> 00:00:40.744
So what causes atelectasis?

13
00:00:41.224 --> 00:00:44.185
It typically falls into three main
categories.

14
00:00:45.185 --> 00:00:49.365
Obstructive, where something like mucus
plugging blocks airflow and causes

15
00:00:49.365 --> 00:00:50.224
distal collapse.

16
00:00:51.025 --> 00:00:54.284
Compressive, where external pressure, like
pleural

17
00:00:54.284 --> 00:00:57.965
effusion or pneumothorax, prevents lung
expansion.

18
00:00:58.705 --> 00:01:03.865
And adhesive, where surfactant dysfunction
allows alveoli to collapse more

19
00:01:03.865 --> 00:01:07.084
easily, often seen in conditions like
ARDS.

20
00:01:08.485 --> 00:01:11.644
Clinically, patients may present with
decreased breath sounds,

21
00:01:12.305 --> 00:01:15.144
crackles, or even silent areas depending
on severity.

22
00:01:15.144 --> 00:01:18.625
You might see increased work of breathing,
tachypnea,

23
00:01:19.105 --> 00:01:20.904
and declining oxygen saturation.

24
00:01:21.684 --> 00:01:24.904
On imaging, look for signs like lung
volume loss,

25
00:01:25.544 --> 00:01:29.264
mediastinal shift toward the affected
side, or areas of increased

26
00:01:29.264 --> 00:01:29.705
density.

27
00:01:30.444 --> 00:01:32.785
Here's the key RT mindset shift.

28
00:01:33.584 --> 00:01:36.004
Atelectasis is not just a diagnosis.

29
00:01:36.665 --> 00:01:38.285
It's a recruitment problem.

30
00:01:38.885 --> 00:01:42.144
Your goal is to reopen alveoli and keep
them open.

31
00:01:42.144 --> 00:01:45.805
That means focusing on lung expansion
therapies.

32
00:01:46.565 --> 00:01:49.324
Incentive spirometry, CPAP, PEEP,

33
00:01:49.944 --> 00:01:54.184
early mobilization, and effective
secretion clearance all play a role.

34
00:01:54.544 --> 00:01:58.065
If the cause is mucus plugging, airway
clearance becomes your

35
00:01:58.065 --> 00:01:58.565
priority.

36
00:01:59.385 --> 00:02:02.705
If it's post-op shallow breathing, pain
control and deep

37
00:02:02.705 --> 00:02:04.425
breathing exercises are critical.

38
00:02:05.285 --> 00:02:09.804
Red flags include worsening hypoxemia,
increasing work of breathing,

39
00:02:10.024 --> 00:02:12.645
or failure to improve with initial
interventions.

40
00:02:13.384 --> 00:02:14.585
That's when you escalate.

41
00:02:15.485 --> 00:02:18.565
Consider non-invasive support or further
diagnostic evaluation.

42
00:02:19.384 --> 00:02:22.345
For board exams, remember this,
atelectasis

43
00:02:22.345 --> 00:02:26.024
equals alveolar collapse, decreased lung
volumes,

44
00:02:26.404 --> 00:02:27.625
and shunt physiology.

45
00:02:28.565 --> 00:02:30.884
Treatment is all about recruitment and
prevention.

46
00:02:31.304 --> 00:02:35.744
As an RT, you are the frontline defense
against atelectasis.

47
00:02:35.744 --> 00:02:39.244
Your assessments, interventions, and
patient coaching

48
00:02:39.244 --> 00:02:41.225
directly impact outcomes.

